--- body ---
## Context

`_CITATION_PERMUTATION_DRIVERS` in `compute_null_model.py` covers only G2
(spectral gap) and G9 (community JS). G1 and G3–G8 have no null model driver,
so their zoo figures show the flat ±2 fallback ribbon. All seven share the same
graph-permutation pattern as G2 and G9: build a union graph for each (year,
window), shuffle which nodes are "before" vs "after", recompute the method's
statistic on each permutation.

## Per-method statistic and permutation structure

| Method | Observed statistic | Permutation target |
|--------|-------------------|-------------------|
| G1 PageRank | `_compare_pagerank_distributions(pr_before, pr_after, n_bins)` — histogram divergence of PageRank vectors | Permute node-to-window assignment in union graph; recompute PageRank on each subgraph |
| G5 Pref attachment | Absolute difference in power-law exponent of in-degree distribution | Permute node-to-window in union graph; recompute exponent on each subgraph |
| G6 Entropy | `abs(_citation_entropy(G_after) − _citation_entropy(G_before))` | Permute node-to-window; recompute entropy on each subgraph |
| G8 Betweenness | `abs(_mean_betweenness(G_after) − _mean_betweenness(G_before))` | Permute node-to-window in union graph; recompute betweenness on each subgraph |

G3, G4, G7 are cumulative per-year methods — split to ticket 0110.

## Actions

1. Add one `_gN_one_window(y, w, works, internal_edges, n_perm, seed, ...)` and
   one `_run_gN_permutations(works, internal_edges, div_df, cfg, n_jobs=-1)`
   per method, following the G2/G9 pattern in `compute_null_model.py`.

2. Register all seven in `_CITATION_PERMUTATION_DRIVERS`:
   ```python
   _CITATION_PERMUTATION_DRIVERS = {
       "G1_pagerank":       _run_g1_permutations,
       "G2_spectral":       _run_g2_spectral_permutations,
       "G5_pref_attachment":_run_g5_permutations,
       "G6_entropy":        _run_g6_permutations,
       "G8_betweenness":    _run_g8_permutations,
       "G9_community":      _run_g9_community_permutations,
   }
   ```

3. Add zoo.mk dependency-only lines for the seven new null CSVs (pattern rule
   already handles the `--null-ci` argument via `$(wildcard ...)`).

4. Run all four on padme and commit the resulting CSVs.

## Implementation order

Order: G6, G8 (pure abs-diff of a graph scalar — trivial G2 clone). Then G5 (power-law fit). Then G1 (PageRank takes two subgraphs, like G9). G8 betweenness: flag that betweenness inside a permutation loop is slow — use k-approximation or a smaller n_perm.

## Test

```python
def test_g1_null_smoke(tmp_path):
    # CLIMATE_FINANCE_DATA=tests/fixtures/smoke
    result = subprocess.run(
        ["uv", "run", "python", "scripts/compute_null_model.py",
         "--method", "G1_pagerank",
         "--div-csv", "content/tables/tab_div_G1_pagerank.csv",
         "--output", str(tmp_path / "tab_null_G1.csv")],
        capture_output=True, text=True
    )
    assert result.returncode == 0
    df = pd.read_csv(tmp_path / "tab_null_G1.csv")
    assert df["null_std"].gt(0).any()
```

Write analogous smoke tests for G5, G6, G8.

## Exit criteria

1. G1, G5, G6, G8 run to completion on the smoke fixture.
2. All four run to completion on the full corpus (padme).
3. Four `tab_null_G*.csv` files committed.
4. `make zoo-figures` shows ribbons for G1, G5, G6, G8.
5. Smoke tests pass under `make check-fast`.
